            'zh-CN': "**技术原理**\n\n分区曝光法由传奇摄影师安塞尔·亚当斯(Ansel Adams)与弗雷德·阿彻(Fred Archer)于1930年代开发。这个系统将照片的明暗范围划分为11个区域(Zone 0-X):\n\n• **Zone 0**: 纯黑,无任何细节\n• **Zone III**: 深灰,阴影中有细节\n• **Zone V**: 中灰(18%灰),测光表的标准值\n• **Zone VII**: 浅灰,高光中有细节\n• **Zone X**: 纯白,无任何细节\n\n这个系统的核心概念是『预视化』(Previsualization),摄影师在按下快门前就能预测最终成品的色调分布。\n\n**实际应用场景**\n\n• 黑白风景摄影:精确控制天空、山脉、前景的色调层次\n• 建筑摄影:确保建筑物细节在高反差环境中完整保留\n• 人像摄影:控制肤色落在理想的Zone VI-VII区间\n• 产品摄影:确保产品质感和细节完美呈现\n\n**参数设定建议**\n\n• 测光时对准想要落在Zone V的区域\n• 如果希望该区域更亮,增加曝光(如Zone VII需+2EV)\n• 如果希望该区域更暗,减少曝光(如Zone III需-2EV)\n• 数位摄影中,可透过RAW档后制调整各区域\n\n**常见误区**\n\n✗ 误区:分区曝光法只适用于底片摄影\n✓ 正解:数位摄影同样适用,直方图就是现代版的分区系统\n\n✗ 误区:必须严格遵守11个区域\n✓ 正解:这是一个思考框架,重点是理解明暗关系\n\n✗ 误区:分区曝光法过于复杂\n✓ 正解:核心概念很简单:测光、预视、调整曝光",
            'en': "**Technical Principles**\n\nThe Zone System was developed by legendary photographer Ansel Adams and Fred Archer in the 1930s. This system divides the tonal range of a photograph into 11 zones (Zone 0-X):\n\n• **Zone 0**: Pure black, no detail\n• **Zone III**: Dark gray, shadow detail visible\n• **Zone V**: Middle gray (18% gray), light meter standard\n• **Zone VII**: Light gray, highlight detail visible\n• **Zone X**: Pure white, no detail\n\nThe core concept is 'Previsualization' - photographers can predict the final tonal distribution before pressing the shutter.\n\n**Practical Applications**\n\n• Black & White Landscape: Precisely control tonal gradation of sky, mountains, foreground\n• Architectural Photography: Preserve building details in high-contrast environments\n• Portrait Photography: Control skin tones to fall in ideal Zone VI-VII range\n• Product Photography: Ensure perfect texture and detail rendering\n\n**Recommended Settings**\n\n• Meter the area you want to place in Zone V\n• To make it brighter, increase exposure (Zone VII needs +2EV)\n• To make it darker, decrease exposure (Zone III needs -2EV)\n• In digital photography, adjust zones in RAW post-processing\n\n**Common Misconceptions**\n\n✗ Myth: Zone System only works for film photography\n✓ Truth: Equally applicable to digital; histogram is the modern zone system\n\n✗ Myth: Must strictly follow 11 zones\n✓ Truth: It's a thinking framework; focus is understanding tonal relationships\n\n✗ Myth: Zone System is too complex\n✓ Truth: Core concept is simple: meter, previsualize, adjust exposure",
